        "body": "<a href="#"><img alt="P2" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p2.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **Containerized MCP server re-downloads package on every restart**

The `docker run --rm` command removes the container (and its writable layer) when the MCP server process exits. Since `npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem` downloads the package into the _container's_ npm cache (`/root/.npm`), that cache is discarded on every restart. Each time Moltis's crash-recovery logic restarts the MCP server, a fresh container is spawned and the package is re-downloaded from npm.

This adds latency on every restart and breaks in air-gapped or rate-limited environments. Consider adding a note suggesting users either pre-build a custom image with the package baked in, or mount a host-side npm cache:

```toml
[mcp.servers.filesystem]
command = "docker"
args = [
  "run", "--rm", "-i",
  # Cache npm downloads across restarts
  "-v", "moltis-npx-cache:/root/.npm",
  "-v", "/data:/data",
  "--entrypoint", "npx",
  "node:22-alpine",
  "-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "/data",
]
```",
        "author": {
          "login": "greptile-apps"
        },
        "createdAt": "2026-03-24T11:08:15Z"
      }
    ]
  }
}

